english:
  title: 'After the Winter Solstice: Second Month, Entering the Retreat, Sent to Jasim of the Jingyuan'
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Old age and sickness have drained my spirit dry.
    At dawn I draw the bronze brazier close, feeling the swift years slip past.
    After the sun turns southward, the daylight at last begins to lengthen,
    Yet when the north wind comes, it threatens to tear my quilted robe.
    I barricade the cold with paper screens and sit alone,
    Then steal warmth from the wooden stove and sink into peaceful sleep.
    Still, the poet's refined taste remains—
    I call for the finest tribute tea, steeped in tears of melted snow.
  footnotes:
    - The winter solstice marks the southernmost point of the sun's path; after this day, daylight gradually increases, symbolizing renewal and hope.
    - 龍團 (tribute tea) refers to the highest grade of ancient Chinese tea, pressed into dragon-shaped cakes—a luxury associated with scholarly refinement.
    - The phrase 'steeped in tears' suggests the speaker's melancholy joy; despite hardship, aesthetic and spiritual pleasures endure.
